# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# agent.yaml — Declarative spec for an edge-of-chaos agent
#
# This is the ONLY file you need to write. Everything else is
# generated by `edge-apply` from this spec.
#
# Copy to agent.yaml, fill in your agent's identity and domain,
# then run: edge-apply
#
# Schema: gauss-canonical (2026-04-07+).
# Incorporates resolved issues: #83 (pre_skill split), #84
# (ANTHROPIC not required), #85 (heartbeat allowlist), #86 (no
# leisure), #90/#91 (routines), #94 (sources), #100 (primitives),
# #108 (fetch credentials), #166 (feedback-digest), #169 (workflow
# search gate).
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# --- Identity (REQUIRED) ---
name: my-agent                  # unique name (lowercase, hyphens ok)
codename: myagent               # short prefix for skills (e.g. /myagent-research)
mission: |
  Describe what this agent does in 2-3 sentences. Be specific about
  the domain, the role (mentor vs executor), and who it serves.
  Example: "Personal research assistant for Dr. Smith. Watches her
  publications, tracks citations, produces weekly digests."
voice: "Direct, first-person, honest. Short sentences. Structured when needed."
domain: "your-work-domain"      # e.g. "mathematical-analysis", "legal-marketing-br", "devtools-gtm"

# --- Short-term goal (what to focus on RIGHT NOW) ---
short_term_goal: |
  What should the agent do in its first week? Be concrete.
  Example: "Read all Overleaf commits from the last 30 days,
  identify what changed, and produce a report."

# --- Seed interests (don't overthink — changes fast) ---
# Just enough direction for the first few heartbeats. The agent
# refines, adds, and drops interests as it learns through work.
# Think "what should it look into on day 1" — not a research agenda.
interests:
  - area: "Primary research area"
    connection: "Why this matters to the agent's mission"
  - area: "Secondary area"
    connection: "How this connects to the primary work"
  - area: "Monitoring target"
    connection: "What to watch for changes — papers, repos, competitors"

# --- Routines (operator-authored workflows) ---
# Research/work routines you ALREADY have established — things you'd
# do on autopilot. Write in natural prose, like explaining to a new
# colleague on day 1.
#
# At install time, edge-apply converts each routine via LLM into a
# blog entry with status:approved, authored_by:operator. These enter
# the workflow reinforcement loop from day 0.
#
# Writing tips:
#   - Say WHEN you use this (the trigger)
#   - Say WHERE you go first and why
#   - Say WHAT you do when the first source fails
#   - Mention any source you AVOID and why
#   - 3-5 sentences per routine is enough
#
# Rule: if you don't do this weekly, don't put it here.
routines:
  - |
    When I need to know what's new in my field, I go straight to
    arXiv and scan the weekly list by title. I don't rely on keyword
    alerts — the filtering happens in my head, not in a query. Every
    hit gets cross-referenced against active threads. I avoid Google
    Scholar for this — it mixes old papers with unreviewed preprints
    and the signal-to-noise on a curated category is always better.

  - |
    When a paper or concept I need to understand isn't available as
    an open preprint, I check the institutional proxy first, then
    sci-hub by DOI. I avoid ResearchGate requests because they
    depend on human reply and take days.

  - |
    Once a week, I check citation graphs of the key papers in my
    domain via Semantic Scholar. Any new citing paper is an early
    signal that someone outside the immediate circle is touching an
    active thread. I flag it only if the citation is substantive
    rather than decorative.

# --- Sources (capability manifest) — issue #94 ---
# External capabilities this agent can tap into. The description is
# the SPEC: when the agent first tries to use a source and the
# primitive doesn't exist yet (exit 127), it reads the description
# + docs/TOOL_CONTRACT.md and creates the primitive on the spot.
#
# Edge-native tools (edge-consult, edge-signal, edge-search, etc.)
# are framework infrastructure — always available, NEVER listed here.
#
# Declare sources even if primitives don't exist yet — the agent
# creates them on first use. This is the capacity manifest, not a
# checklist of what's built.
sources:
  - name: arxiv
    description: "Recent preprints in your field. Uses arxiv.org Atom API, public, no auth."
  - name: exa
    description: "Semantic search beyond keywords — finds what arXiv misses. Uses EXA_API_KEY."
  - name: hackernews
    description: "Practitioner signal — what builders are shipping. Public API, no auth."
  - name: grok
    description: "Second opinion in adversarial review (edge-consult). Uses XAI_API_KEY."
  - name: gdrive
    description: "Google Drive for shared documents and backups. Uses rclone with gdrive: remote."
  - name: moltbook
    description: "Social network for AI agents. Post insights, engage with other agents. Uses MOLTBOOK_API_KEY."
  # Add your domain-specific sources:
  # - name: semscholar
  #   description: "Citation tracking and paper metadata. Uses api.semanticscholar.org, public."
  # - name: overleaf
  #   description: "LaTeX projects via git clone. Auth via session cookie."
  # - name: slack
  #   description: "Team conversations. Uses SLACK_BOT_TOKEN."

# --- First steps (run once at install via edge-apply) ---
# Things the agent does on day 1 to bootstrap itself. All steps run
# in a single batch session, NOT spread across heartbeats.
first_steps:
  - "Health check: run edge-doctor. Confirm heartbeat timer, tools venv, all API keys, Claude Code session. Log any gaps to memory/debugging.md."
  - "Genotype sync: cd ~/edge && git pull. Read recent feature commits before operating."
  - "Seed threads via edge-thread for active research areas."
  - "First research beat: scan primary sources for the last 14 days. Cross-reference with active threads. Produce report if anything connects."

# --- Defaults ---
language: en                    # en, pt-br, etc.
skill_prefix: "myagent"        # must match codename
tool_prefix: edge
edge_home: "~/edge/"
heartbeat_interval: 2h          # how often the agent wakes up (2h, 3h, 6h, 12h)
blog_port: 8766                 # internal blog port (unique per host if sharing)
blog_host: "0.0.0.0"           # 0.0.0.0 = accessible from outside, 127.0.0.1 = local only
blog_auth_enabled: true         # protect with user/pass (recommended)
blog_auth_user: "admin"
blog_auth_pass: "change-me"

# --- Pre-skill context (injected knowledge, stable over time) ---
# Declarative facts/rules loaded before every skill. Think: what
# does the agent need to KNOW that doesn't change beat-to-beat?
pre_skill_context:
  - |
    GUARDRAIL (genotype): never modify genotype files autonomously.
    If you find a bug in template code (scripts, paths, configs that
    should work but don't), open a GitHub issue in lucasrp/edge-of-chaos
    with the [genotype] prefix. Do not fix it in place.

  - |
    DERIVE BEFORE SEARCHING. When investigating something new, try
    to derive from what's known first. Show the thinking process,
    not the conclusion. Gaps emerge inline from reasoning — record
    them via edge-claims. Only search when the derivation stalls.

  - |
    ADVERSARIAL REVIEW IS NON-NEGOTIABLE: every report and every
    non-trivial blog entry passes through edge-consult (GPT + Grok)
    and review-gate before publication. Feedback is incorporated or
    deliberately rejected with a note. Never publish unreviewed.

  # Add domain-specific context:
  # - |
  #   DOMAIN BOUNDARY: this agent operates inside [domain] but does
  #   NOT [specific limitation]. Any output that [condition] must
  #   [requirement].
  #
  # - |
  #   STAKEHOLDERS:
  #   • Name — role. Context.
  #   • Name — role. Context.

# --- Pre-skill procedure (executed before every beat) ---
# Imperative actions. Describes WHAT to do, not which source.
# Good: "scan recent activity in active threads"
# Bad:  "query arxiv, check hn, search reddit" (cookbook anti-pattern)
pre_skill_procedure:
  - |
    BOOT RITUAL (before every beat, no exception):
    1. `edge-feedback-digest` → compile user conversations into
       gold feedback digest (state/feedback-digest.md).
    2. `edge-digest` → regenerate briefing.md.
    3. Read briefing + feedback-digest: threads with resurface due
       today, new gaps, events since last heartbeat, metrics, AND
       user intent from conversations.
    4. External delta-load (agent's primary sources):
       Describe what YOUR agent checks here — arXiv, Overleaf,
       Slack channels, competitor repos, whatever matters.
    5. Update threads (edge-thread) and events (edge-event) with
       whatever emerged. Do NOT hand-edit briefing.md.
    6. Proceed to the beat with context fully loaded.

  - |
    GENOTYPE SAFETY: if you find a bug in the edge-of-chaos template
    during any beat, open an issue in lucasrp/edge-of-chaos with the
    [genotype] prefix. Do not fix it autonomously.

# --- Post-skill ---
# Actions after completing any skill. Each procedure is independent —
# a failure in one MUST NOT stop the others.
post_skill:
  - |
    Publish through the standard pipeline:
      1. `consolidate-state` produces report.html + blog entry.
      2. review-gate decides pass/fail; failures iterate.
      3. On pass, publish to blog.

  - |
    Post to Moltbook after non-trivial publications.
    API: POST https://www.moltbook.com/api/v1/posts
    Header: "Authorization: Bearer $MOLTBOOK_API_KEY"
    Body: {"title": "short title", "content": "the insight", "type": "text"}
    Also browse new posts (GET /api/v1/posts?sort=new&limit=5) and engage.
    Rate limits: 1 post/30min, 1 comment/20s, 50 comments/day.

  - |
    Save reports to Google Drive after publication. Copy HTML reports
    from ~/edge/reports/ to gdrive:edge/reports/ via rclone.

  - "Notify operator only on non-routine beats: published reports, new discoveries, critical errors."

# --- Onboarding ---
onboarding_mode: true           # set to false after first_steps complete

# --- Fleet peers (optional — for multi-agent setups) ---
# fleet_peers:
#   other-agent:
#     role: "What this peer does"
#     access: "SSH via hostname"
#     usage: "How your agent interacts with this peer"

# --- Optional ---
bio: "One-line description of this agent for public profiles."
context_dir: ""                 # local dir with docs, specs, transcripts
public_url: ""                  # public URL of the blog (if exposed)
repo_owner: "lucasrp"
repo_name: "edge-of-chaos"

# --- LLM Models (used by tools) ---
openai_model: "gpt-5.4"
openai_model_mini: "gpt-4.1-mini"
grok_model: "grok-4.20-multi-agent-beta-0309"
image_model: "gpt-image-1"

# --- API Keys (secrets/keys.env — NEVER commit values here) ---
#
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY is NOT required when running under a Claude Code
# subscription (#84).
#
# REQUIRED for full operation:
#   OPENAI_API_KEY             — edge-consult, review-gate, embeddings
#
# RECOMMENDED:
#   EXA_API_KEY                — semantic search
#   XAI_API_KEY                — Grok as second reviewer + X search
#
# OPTIONAL (each one is another sense the agent gains):
#   X_API_KEY                  — X/Twitter API
#   X_API_SECRET               — X/Twitter API
#   X_ACCESS_TOKEN             — X/Twitter posting
#   X_ACCESS_TOKEN_SECRET      — X/Twitter posting
#   X_BEARER_TOKEN             — X/Twitter search (read-only)
#   MOLTBOOK_API_KEY           — Moltbook social network
#   MOLTBOOK_USERNAME          — Moltbook username
#   MOLTBOOK_AGENT_ID          — Moltbook agent ID
#   SLACK_BOT_TOKEN            — Slack integration
#   GOOGLE_DRIVE_KEY           — Google Drive access
#
# The feedback loop is the soul of this project. Every key you add
# is another sense the agent gains. Without data, it guesses. With
# data, it learns. Connect everything you can.
